snippet.textDisplay: I was a lot like you this time last year, Mark (minus the YouTube stardom and casual lunches with Bill Gates, of course). I ate meat with basically every single meal, and considered no plate complete without it. At the same time I had been growing increasingly aware of my environmental impact, and watched some Kurzgesagt videos about the meat industry and meat consumption. I was kind of shocked and made the change, initially, to go meatless during the week, figuring that if someone like me couldn't make a change like that, any talk on reverting environmental damage was probably a non-starter. I'm not going to preach to anyone about going meatless full-time because I do still believe there are benefits to having a balanced diet, but I wanted to say thanks for making this video anyway. Sparking some interest in people to go meatless, even if only once a week, could have quite the ripple.

snippet.textDisplay:
What I've always had trouble with, is the overall comparison of live stock resources versus. alternatives.
We do know by now, based on research, that in isolation, the alternatives always win. But what about when you consider the whole?


Yes, a kilogram of meat requires over 5000 liters of water, but considering that water was in part consumed directly by the cow to grow until it was slaughtered, what about the byproducts? That water didn't only grow the cow's meat, it also grew their bones (used for gelatin and its byproducts), their hide (leather and its byproducts), potentially milk the cow provided (and byproducts, like cheese, ice cream, butter, etc).


When you sum up all the alternatives to those products, like vegan leather, vegetable based 'meat', gelatin alternative, vegetable based 'milk', etc. in equal quantities than the whole cow provided during its lifespan, how does the comparison come out (as in water used, energy consumed, emissions released, etc)?
I would assume the alternatives win, but I'd also assume the margin is considerably narrower than you'd think after seeing a video like this one. They always talk about certain products in isolation (like livestock meat) but not all the other products that also come out of the livestock, combined.
